From: aorus-5090-egpu <noreply@example.invalid>
Date: 2026-05-08
Subject: [PATCH] AORUS Patch 0027 — dispatch slot_reset+resume from work handler

After pci_reset_bus succeeds, the work handler now explicitly
invokes tb_egpu_lever_m_slot_reset() and (on RECOVERED)
tb_egpu_lever_m_slot_reset_resume(), so the manual trigger path
(post-rmInit-FAIL hook + sysfs force_trigger) reaches the same
completion state as the AER PCI_ERS_RESULT_NEED_RESET path.

Why this is necessary:

  pci_reset_bus() resets the secondary bus but does NOT dispatch
  through pci_error_handlers->slot_reset / ->resume. Those
  callbacks only fire when the AER subsystem drives recovery via
  the NEED_RESET return path from error_detected. Until this patch,
  the manual trigger path completed the bus reset but never ran
  PMC_BOOT_0 verification, never incremented success_count, never
  reset attempt_count, and never emitted TB_EGPU_GPU_STATE=READY.

  In production, the WPR2-stuck recovery (the very case Lever M-
  recover targets) comes through the post-rmInit-FAIL hook, NOT
  through AER. So the bug was production-relevant, not a
  test-only concern.

  Discovered while preparing Phase 3 manual-trigger testing
  (Patch 0026's sysfs force_trigger): the expected dmesg trail
  showed only the bus-reset half, no slot_reset/resume.

Behaviour after this patch:

  - Manual trigger path: schedule_work -> pci_reset_bus -> our
    slot_reset helper (PMC_BOOT_0 read; RECOVERED or DISCONNECT)
    -> our resume helper (success_count++, attempt_count=0,
    TB_EGPU_GPU_STATE=READY uevent) on RECOVERED. Surrender
    accounting in slot_reset handles the DISCONNECT branch.

  - AER NEED_RESET path: unchanged. The kernel still drives the
    bus reset and dispatches our slot_reset/resume helpers via
    err_handlers. Our work handler is NOT invoked on that path.

No double-dispatch: pci_reset_bus does not invoke err_handlers
callbacks, and the kernel does not synthesise an AER event from
a manual reset, so the helpers run exactly once per recovery.
---
--- a/kernel-open/nvidia/nv-lever-m-recover.c
+++ b/kernel-open/nvidia/nv-lever-m-recover.c
@@ -270,10 +270,27 @@
     }
 
     nv_printf(NV_DBG_ERRORS,
-        "AORUS Lever M-recover: pci_reset_bus(%s) OK; awaiting slot_reset/"
-        "resume callbacks for verification + counter reset\n",
+        "AORUS Lever M-recover: pci_reset_bus(%s) OK; dispatching "
+        "slot_reset + resume helpers explicitly\n",
         pci_name(bridge));
 
+    /* Patch 0027: pci_reset_bus does NOT dispatch err_handlers->slot_reset
+     * or ->resume callbacks — those only fire when the AER subsystem
+     * drives recovery via PCI_ERS_RESULT_NEED_RESET. To unify the manual
+     * trigger path (post-rmInit-FAIL hook + sysfs force_trigger) with the
+     * AER path so both finish recovery accounting — PMC_BOOT_0 verify,
+     * success_count++, attempt_count reset to 0, TB_EGPU_GPU_STATE=READY
+     * uevent — we invoke our slot_reset helper here, and on RECOVERED
+     * also the resume helper. Both helpers handle their own logging and
+     * uevent emission. The DISCONNECT branch's surrender accounting is
+     * handled inside tb_egpu_lever_m_slot_reset(). */
+    {
+        pci_ers_result_t rs = tb_egpu_lever_m_slot_reset(pdev);
+        if (rs == PCI_ERS_RESULT_RECOVERED) {
+            tb_egpu_lever_m_slot_reset_resume(pdev);
+        }
+    }
+
 out_put:
     pci_dev_put(pdev);
     lm->pdev_for_work = NULL;
